    <stitle>RECONDITIONING ROTORS - INSPECTION - GREASE-STAINED ROTORS</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="inspect" graphiccount="1">
        <title>GREASE-STAINED ROTORS</title>
        <para>If oil or grease is splattered on the rotor, the brake rotors will show discolored spots on the braking
            surfaces (
            <hotlnk xrefid="f0401817">Figure 17
                <xref refid="f0401817"/>
            </hotlnk>
            ).
        </para>
        <figure id="f0401817" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g0401817" filename="../figg04/G0401817.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="272px" resolution="72"/>
            <caption>Figure 17. Grease-Stained Rotor</caption>
        </figure>
        <para>It may be caused by a faulty lubrication system or improper greasing of the brake mechanism.</para>
        <para>To correct the problem, you must repair the source of the oil or grease leak. Then, clean the entire brake
            rotor and replace brake pads if they are soaked with oil or grease.
        </para>
    </svcproc>
